Homomorphic encryption is fascinating!
I think the asymetric example you quoted is a bit misleading since the homomorphic systems would ideally make the (de/en)cryption transparent. For example, a service can compute things through your data without having total read access.
This is also what makes it confusing to me since I can't imagine what the primitives or instruction set would look like to make this (partially?) turing complete. I can imagine for instance a counter where only the person with the key can read it and everybody could request updates to it but having counters that can be queried for arbitrary values (`min()/max()` for instance) without decryption sounds fishy to me, as in _how couldn't this leak my data?_ and this is only counters, not to mention set membership or general.
Then again it has been quite some time until I read about it and [zerocash](http://news.yahoo.com/video/yahoo-trust-unconference-zerocash-zooko-222611059.html) seems to get along quite well, too. Maybe it is about tradeoffs and capabilities you want from such a system. I need to reface my low-level daemons and ask them how to construct everything from `and` and `xor`. I'd love to do an experimental crypto co-processor in [pshdl](http://pshdl.org/) for instance but I don't feel strongly versed enough to spec it out.

* Soundcloud - has follow artist/label, previews of tracks, sometimes in full.

* A distributed filesystem for tracks

We got so tired of NATs and firewalls yesterday that we started dialing each other over tor hidden services:

```
# torrc snip
HiddenServiceDir /var/lib/tor/ssb_service/
HiddenServicePort 8008 127.0.0.1:8008
```
which should give you this after restarting tor
```
$ cat /var/lib/tor/ssb_service/hostname 
y2qv6jbg3pzokkqu.onion
```

To connect from another node, sprinkle a little [socat](http://www.dest-unreach.org/socat/) magic on top:

```
$ socat TCP4-LISTEN:$port,fork SOCKS4A:localhost:$my.onion:8008,socksport=9050  
```

and then to let the gossip flow:

```
$ sbot gossip.add localhost:$port:$myFeedID
```

There is probably a screeching privacy leak in using this (might advertise local IPs still?) but it helps __a lot__ when dealing with stupid networks (looking at you, eduroam) and it frees us from depending on pubs.

The socat localhost port juggling won't scale, though...

# Bare with me through this technical trickery to seed your friends today

Like I said above you now have everything we have and that a new user would download if they onboarded through a pub server on the internet. Soo... Like you already guessed: One important thing to understand is that patchwork runs on a local scuttlebot instance (`sbot`) and a pub server is nothing more than a sbot with a public address and all that it does is give you messages you don't already have and copy your new messages for others.

Soooo...! With a small `.ssb/config` tweak\* , you can create invites for your local instance with this command `sbot invite.create 5`\*\*. Then your 5 friends can join your _pub_ and you can seed them all of the data locally over LAN/WiFi and later they connect to a internet pub and their data usage will be minimal since they already have everything there is.

I hope that wasn't way to technical and confusing... If you have questions or problems, please ask!

* http://ssbc.github.io

1) re  mobile: since sbot runs directly on the keyfiles, you open up pandoras box of how to transfer the keys to your other devices, have multiple keys/profiles or proxy/tunnel your mobile UI to a remote system where your keys are stored. The last point is possible today but has it's own issues, mainly remote system compromise and key extraction.

2) re bitlocker: the person in question might want to check if microsoft [has](http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-8/bitlocker-recovery-keys-faq) a backup/recovery version of his disk encryption key files.
I have no doubt these are accessible to gov parties if requested through the right channels (prism, warrent, what ever,...).

IIRC the practice of storing a backup key on Microsofts infrastructure also became default with windows 10 fresh installs. OSX's FileVault also prompts you for this, these days.

Personally, I haven't converted my truecrypt drives to veracrypt because I haven't tested how well vera- works on other platforms than windows, which is what I liked about truecrypt...

Which leaves us with the linux systems cryptfs and luks. I tend to recommend luks when possible just because that's what I heard the least amount of compromise about.

All these still have one more attack vector in common in case of seizure. Search for "Evil Maid Attack" or "bootkit" (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rootkit#bootkit).
In short: your system still needs to boot from unauthenticated clear text stored on an unencrypted partition in most cases*, which leaves an entry point for an attacker to hook your password input when opening your full disk encryption and extract it.

(In most cases*: I only met one human in person so far brave enough to flash his bios with coreboot and I need to read up on TrustedPlatformModule and SecureBoot if this really helps against this.)


3) public messages are secure in that they are signed by your key (no author spoofing). The only thing encrypted on disk are private messages. We are also thinking about opening up gateways into the ssb space so that you can link to posts reachable through legacy web. (Codename: porthole)


All-in-all I'm not sure ssb/patchwork is the right tool for clandestine operation as it stands. There is also the can of worms of time correlations on PMs to see how is messaging with whom.

[secretstream](https://godoc.org/github.com/cryptix/secretstream) is following the go way of doing networking and supplies you with `Listen()` and `Dial()` similar to the [net](https://godoc.org/net) package, so you can also pass it to `net/rpc` or other packages following these interfaces.

[go-muxrpc](https://godoc.org/github.com/cryptix/go-muxrpc) is currently lacking a couple of features (mainly async stream handling and registering handlers for incoming requests) but the packet-stream-codec port is solid. I will update it as I make progress on my higher level tools.

scb (secret cat box) was supposed to be a net-cat like thing uses secretstream but I was too eager to test out sbot interaction. In the linked git tree, you can see how to do request in the commented out `beepBoop()` function, like `createLogStream`. It also allows you to listen on a port and see the incoming requests.
